WEBVTT

00:11.320 --> 00:11.880
XX.

00:15.580 --> 00:16.980
The Minister in a Maze.

00:17.720 --> 00:22.000
As the minister departed, in advance of Hester Prynne and Little Pearl, he threw a backward

00:22.000 --> 00:27.260
glance, half expecting that he should discover only some faintly traced features or outline

00:27.260 --> 00:31.040
of the mother and the child, slowly fading into the twilight of the woods.

00:31.560 --> 00:35.460
So great of a sictitude of his life could not at once be received as real.

00:35.880 --> 00:41.060
But there was Hester, clad in her grey robe, still standing beside the tree trunk, which

00:41.060 --> 00:46.020
some blast had overthrown a long antiquity ago, and which time had ever since been covering

00:46.020 --> 00:51.240
with moss, so that these two fated ones, with earth's heaviest burden on them, might there

00:51.240 --> 00:54.800
sit down together and find a single hour's rest and solace.

00:54.800 --> 00:59.720
And there was Pearl too, lightly dancing from the margin of the brook, now that the intrusive

00:59.720 --> 01:03.160
third person was gone and taking her old place by her mother's side.

01:03.580 --> 01:06.220
So the minister had not fallen asleep and dreamed.

01:07.620 --> 01:12.300
In order to free his mind from this indistinctness and duplicity of impression which vexed it

01:12.300 --> 01:16.860
with a strange disquietude, he recalled and more thoroughly defined the plans which Hester

01:16.860 --> 01:18.900
and himself had sketched for their departure.

01:19.420 --> 01:24.280
It had been determined between them that the old world, with its crowds and cities, offered

01:24.280 --> 01:29.040
them a more eligible shelter and concealment than the wilds of New England or all America,

01:29.300 --> 01:33.720
with its alternatives of an Indian wigwam where the few settlements of Europeans scattered

01:33.720 --> 01:35.040
thinly along the seaboard.

01:35.440 --> 01:39.760
Not to speak of the clergyman's health, so inadequate to sustain the hardships of a forest

01:39.760 --> 01:45.140
life, his native gifts, his culture, and his entire development would secure him a home

01:45.140 --> 01:47.900
only in the midst of civilization and refinement.

01:48.680 --> 01:52.080
The higher the state, the more delicately adapted to it the man.

01:52.730 --> 01:57.360
In furtherance of this choice, it so happened that a ship lay in the harbor, one of those

01:57.360 --> 02:02.780
unquestionable cruisers frequent at that day, with, without being absolutely outlaws of

02:02.780 --> 02:07.520
the deep, yet roamed over its surface with a remarkable irresponsibility of character.

02:08.020 --> 02:12.320
This vessel had recently arrived from the Spanish main, and within three days' time

02:12.320 --> 02:13.420
would sail for Bristol.

02:14.040 --> 02:19.320
Hester Prynne, whose vocation, as a self-enlisted sister of charity, had brought her acquainted

02:19.320 --> 02:23.540
with the captain and crew, could take upon herself to secure the passage of two individuals

02:23.540 --> 02:28.100
and a child with all the secrecy which circumstances rendered more than desirable.

02:29.580 --> 02:34.140
The minister had inquired of Hester, with no little interest, the precise time at which

02:34.140 --> 02:35.880
the vessel might be expected to depart.

02:36.200 --> 02:38.720
It would probably be on the fourth day from the present.

02:38.980 --> 02:43.860
This is most fortunate, he had said to himself, now, why the Reverend Mr. Dimseyle considered

02:43.860 --> 02:46.080
it so very fortunate we hesitate to reveal.

02:46.660 --> 02:50.760
Nevertheless, to hold nothing back from the reader, it was because, on the third day from

02:50.760 --> 02:55.720
the present, he was to preach the election sermon, and, as such an occasion formed an

02:55.720 --> 02:59.860
honorable epoch in the life of a New England clergyman, he could not have chanced upon

02:59.860 --> 03:03.420
a more suitable mode and time of terminating his professional career.

03:03.700 --> 03:09.140
At last they shall say of me, thought this exemplary man, that I leave no duty unperformed

03:09.140 --> 03:10.020
or ill-performed.

03:10.500 --> 03:15.280
Sad, indeed, that an introspection so profound and acute as this poor minister's should be

03:15.280 --> 03:16.320
so miserably deceived.

03:16.660 --> 03:21.660
We have had, and may still have, worse things to tell of him, but none, we apprehend, so

03:21.660 --> 03:26.780
pitably weak, no evidence, at once so slight and irrefragable, of a subtle disease that

03:26.780 --> 03:30.060
had long since begun to eat into the real substance of his character.

03:30.560 --> 03:35.440
No man, for any considerable period, can wear one face to himself and another to the multitude,

03:35.860 --> 03:39.180
without finally getting bewildered as to which may be the true.

03:40.340 --> 03:44.900
The excitement of Mr. Dimseyle's feelings as he returned from his interview with Hester

03:44.900 --> 03:49.220
lent him an unaccustomed physical energy, and hurried him townward at a rapid pace.

03:49.740 --> 03:54.740
The pathway along the woods seemed wilder, more uncouth with its rude natural obstacles,

03:55.100 --> 03:58.600
and less trodden by the foot of man than he remembered it on his outward journey.

03:59.040 --> 04:04.100
But he leaped across the plashy places, thrust himself through the clinging underbrush, climbed

04:04.100 --> 04:09.780
the ascent, plunged into the hollow, and overcame, in short, all of the difficulties of the track,

04:10.100 --> 04:13.220
with an unwaryable activity that astonished him.

04:13.220 --> 04:18.220
He could not but recall how feebly, and with what frequent pauses for breath, he had toiled

04:18.220 --> 04:20.320
over the same ground only two days before.

04:20.800 --> 04:25.200
As he drew near the town, he took an impression of change from the series of familiar objects

04:25.200 --> 04:26.260
that presented themselves.

04:26.660 --> 04:31.800
It seemed not yesterday, not one, not two, but many days, or even years ago, since he

04:31.800 --> 04:32.480
had quitted them.

04:32.900 --> 04:37.780
There indeed was each former trace of the street as he remembered it, and all the peculiarities

04:37.780 --> 04:42.880
of the house, with the due multitude of gabled peaks, and a weathercock at every point where

04:42.880 --> 04:44.180
his memory suggested one.

04:44.760 --> 04:48.700
Not the less, however, came this importunately obtrusive sense of change.

04:49.080 --> 04:54.500
The same was true as regarded the acquaintances whom he met, and all the well-known shapes

04:54.500 --> 04:56.340
of human life, about the little town.

04:56.600 --> 04:58.400
They looked neither old nor young now.

04:58.540 --> 05:02.620
The beards of the aged were no whiter, nor could the creeping babe of yesterday walk

05:02.620 --> 05:03.440
on his feet today.

05:03.800 --> 05:08.500
It was impossible to describe in what respect they differed from the individuals on whom

05:08.500 --> 05:10.660
he had so recently bestowed a parting glance.

05:10.660 --> 05:15.220
And yet the minister's deepest sense seemed to inform him of their mutability.

05:16.080 --> 05:20.660
A similar impression struck him most remarkably as he passed under the walls of his own church.

05:21.080 --> 05:26.060
The edifice had so very strange, and yet so familiar an aspect, that Mr. Dimmesdale's

05:26.060 --> 05:31.800
mind vibrated between two ideas, either that he had seen it only in a dream hitherto, or

05:31.800 --> 05:33.580
that he was merely dreaming about it now.

05:34.040 --> 05:38.940
This phenomenon, in the various shapes which it assumed, indicated no external change,

05:38.940 --> 05:44.260
but so sudden and important a change in the spectator of the familiar scene that the intervening

05:44.260 --> 05:48.660
space of a single day had operated on his consciousness like the lapse of years.

05:49.140 --> 05:53.860
The minister's own will, and Hester's will, and the fate that grew between them, had wrought

05:53.860 --> 05:54.740
this transformation.

05:55.220 --> 05:59.840
It was the same town as Heretofore, but the same minister returned not from the forest.

06:00.160 --> 06:04.020
He might have said to the friends who greeted him, I am not the man for whom you take me.

06:04.020 --> 06:09.300
I left him yonder in the forest, withdrawn into a secret dell by a mossy tree-trunk and

06:09.300 --> 06:10.580
near a melancholy brook.

06:10.700 --> 06:16.640
Go seek your minister, and see if his emaciated figure, his thin cheek, his white, heavy,

06:16.840 --> 06:20.340
pain-wrinkled brow, be not flung down there like a cast-off garment.

06:20.760 --> 06:25.860
His friends, no doubt, would still have insisted with him, Thou art thyself the man!

06:26.200 --> 06:29.380
But this error would have been their own, not his.

06:29.740 --> 06:34.400
Before Mr. Dimmesdale reached home, his inner man gave him other evidences of a revolution

06:34.400 --> 06:35.940
in the sphere of thought and feeling.

06:36.340 --> 06:41.740
In truth, nothing short of a total change of dynasty and moral code in that interior

06:41.740 --> 06:47.420
kingdom was adequate to account for the impulses now communicated to the unfortunate and startled

06:47.420 --> 06:47.840
minister.

06:48.280 --> 06:53.800
At every step he was incited to do something strange, wild, wicked thing or other, with

06:53.800 --> 07:01.000
at once, involuntary and intentional, in spite of himself, yet growing out of a profounder

07:01.000 --> 07:03.060
self than that which opposed the impulse.

07:03.380 --> 07:05.600
For instance, he met one of his own deacons.

07:06.000 --> 07:10.120
The good old man addressed himself with the paternal affection and patriarchal privilege

07:10.120 --> 07:15.400
which his venerable age, his upright and holy character, and his station in the church entitled

07:15.400 --> 07:20.680
him to use, and, conjoined with this, the deep, almost worshipping respect which the

07:20.680 --> 07:23.180
minister's professional and private claims alike demanded.

07:23.900 --> 07:28.820
Never was there a more beautiful example of how the majesty of age and wisdom may comport

07:28.820 --> 07:35.140
with this obscenes and respect enjoined upon it, as from the lower social rank and inferior

07:35.140 --> 07:37.160
order of endowment towards a higher.

07:37.760 --> 07:42.440
Now, during a conversation of some two or three moments between the Reverend Mr. Dimmesdale

07:42.440 --> 07:47.320
and this excellent and hoary-bearded deacon, it was only by the most careful self-control

07:47.320 --> 07:51.500
that the former could refrain from uttering certain blasphemous suggestions that rose

07:51.500 --> 07:53.980
into his mind, respecting the communion supper.

07:54.360 --> 07:58.860
He absolutely trembled and turned pale as ashes, lest his tongue should wag itself

07:58.860 --> 08:03.320
in utterance of these horrible matters, and plead his own consent for so doing without

08:03.320 --> 08:08.000
his having fairly given it, and, even with this terror in his heart, he could hardly

08:08.000 --> 08:13.280
avoid laughing to imagine how the sanctified old patriarchal deacon would have been petrified

08:13.280 --> 08:14.640
by his minister's impiety.

08:15.640 --> 08:17.920
Again, another incident of the same nature.

08:18.280 --> 08:22.480
Hurrying along the street, the Reverend Dimmesdale encountered the eldest female member of his

08:22.480 --> 08:28.280
church, a most pious and exemplary old dame, poor, widowed, lonely, and with a heart full

08:28.280 --> 08:33.540
of reminisces about her dead husband and children, and her dead friends of long ago, as a burial

08:33.540 --> 08:35.540
ground is full of stored gravestones.

08:35.840 --> 08:40.540
Yet all this, which would else have been such heavy sorrow, was made almost a solemn joy

08:40.540 --> 08:46.340
to her devout old soul by religious consolations and the truth of scripture, wherewith she

08:46.340 --> 08:50.720
had fed herself continually for more than thirty years, and since Mr. Dimmesdale had

08:50.720 --> 08:55.420
taken her in charge, the good grandam's chief earthly comfort, which, unless it had been

08:55.420 --> 08:59.880
likewise a heavenly comfort, could have been none at all, was to meet her pastor, with

08:59.880 --> 09:05.280
her casually or of set purpose, and be refreshed with a word of warm, fragrant, heaven-breathing

09:05.280 --> 09:10.240
gospel truth from his beloved lips into her dulled but rapturously attentive ear.

09:10.860 --> 09:15.240
But on this occasion, up to the moment of putting his lips to the old woman's ear,

09:15.460 --> 09:20.000
Mr. Dimmesdale, as the great enemy of souls would have it, could recall no text of scripture,

09:20.260 --> 09:26.520
nor aught else, except a brief pithy and, as it then appeared to him, unanswerable argument

09:26.520 --> 09:28.660
against the immortality of the human soul.

09:29.260 --> 09:33.780
The instillment thereof into her mind would probably have caused this aged sister to drop

09:33.780 --> 09:37.780
dead at once, as by the effect of an intensely poisonous infusion.

09:38.140 --> 09:41.500
What he really did whisper, the minister could never afterwards recollect.

09:41.680 --> 09:46.020
There was perhaps a fortunate disorder in his utterance, which failed to impart any

09:46.020 --> 09:50.900
distinct idea to the good widow's comprehension, or which Providence interpreted after a method

09:50.900 --> 09:51.440
of its own.

09:52.200 --> 09:56.380
Assuredly, as the minister looked back, he beheld an expression of divine gratitude and

09:56.380 --> 10:01.240
ecstasy that seemed like the shine of a the celestial city on her face, so wrinkled and

10:01.240 --> 10:01.780
ashy pale.

10:02.380 --> 10:06.720
Again, a third instance, after parting from the old church member, he met the youngest

10:06.720 --> 10:07.620
sister of them all.

10:07.840 --> 10:12.660
It was a maiden newly won, and won by the reverend Mr. Dimmesdale's own sermon, on

10:12.660 --> 10:16.720
the Sabbath after his vigil, to barter the transitory pleasures of the world for the

10:16.720 --> 10:21.580
heavenly hope that was to assume brighter substance as life grew dark around her, and

10:21.580 --> 10:24.040
which would gild the utter gloom with final glory.

10:24.440 --> 10:27.860
She was fair and pure, as a lily that had bloomed in paradise.

10:27.860 --> 10:32.760
The minister knew well that he was himself enshrined with the stainless sanctity of her

10:32.760 --> 10:37.520
heart, which hung its snowy curtains about his image, imparting to religion the warmth

10:37.520 --> 10:39.900
of love, and to love a religious purity.

10:40.580 --> 10:45.000
Satan that afternoon had surely led the poor young girl away from her mother's side, and

10:45.000 --> 10:50.180
thrown her into the pathway of this sorely tempted, or, shall we not rather say, this

10:50.180 --> 10:51.500
lost and desperate man.

10:51.680 --> 10:57.200
As she drew nigh, the archfiend whispered him to condense into small compass, and drop

10:57.200 --> 11:02.540
into her tender bosom a germ of evil that would be sure to blossom darkly soon, and

11:02.540 --> 11:04.100
bear black fruit at times.

11:04.420 --> 11:09.660
Such was his sense of power over this virgin soul, trusting him as she did, that the minister

11:09.660 --> 11:15.060
felt potent to blight all the fields of innocence with but one wicked look, and develop all

11:15.060 --> 11:16.480
its opposite with but a word.

11:16.820 --> 11:21.360
So with a mightier struggle than he had yet sustained, he held his Jennifer cloak before

11:21.360 --> 11:26.080
his face, and hurried onward, making no sign of recognition, and leaving the young sister

11:26.080 --> 11:27.900
to digest his rudeness as she might.

11:28.500 --> 11:32.780
She ransacked her conscience, which was full of harmless little matters, like her pocket

11:32.780 --> 11:37.580
or her work-bag, and took herself to task, poor thing, for a thousand imaginary faults,

11:37.840 --> 11:41.220
and went about her household duties with swollen eyelids the next morning.

11:41.680 --> 11:45.880
Before the minister had time to celebrate his victory over this last temptation, he

11:45.880 --> 11:49.480
was conscious of another impulse, more ludicrous and almost as horrible.

11:49.660 --> 11:54.840
It was, we blush to tell it, it was to stop short in the road, and teach some very wicked

11:54.840 --> 11:59.900
words to a knot of little Puritan children, who were playing there, and had just begun

11:59.900 --> 12:00.340
to talk.

12:00.840 --> 12:05.560
Denying himself this freak, as unworthy of his cloth, he met a drunken seaman, one of

12:05.560 --> 12:07.220
the ship's crew from the Spanish main.

12:07.520 --> 12:12.540
And here, since he had so valiantly forebode all other wickedness, poor Mr. Dimmesdale

12:12.540 --> 12:17.880
longed at last to shake hands with this tarry black guard, and recreate himself with a

12:17.880 --> 12:23.360
few improper jests, such as dissolute sailors so abound with, and a volley of good, round,

12:23.360 --> 12:26.220
solid, satisfactory, and heaven-defying oaths.

12:26.220 --> 12:30.780
It was not so much a better principle, as partly his natural good taste, and still more

12:30.780 --> 12:34.980
his buck-rammed habit of clerical decorum, that carried him safely through the latter

12:34.980 --> 12:35.440
crisis.

12:36.240 --> 12:41.180
"'What is it that hurts and tempts me thus?' cried the minister to himself at length, pausing

12:41.180 --> 12:43.560
in the street, and striking his hand against his forehead.

12:43.860 --> 12:47.340
"'Am I mad, or am I giving over utterly to the fiend?

12:47.580 --> 12:50.960
Did I make a contract with him in the forest, and sign it with my blood?

12:50.960 --> 12:55.620
And does he now summon me to its fulfilment, by suggesting the performance of every wickedness

12:55.620 --> 12:58.620
which his most foul imagination can conceive?'

12:58.620 --> 13:02.940
At the moment, when the reverend Mr. Dimmesdale thus communed with himself, and struck his

13:02.940 --> 13:08.040
forehead with his hand, old Mistress Hibbins, the reputed witch-lady, is said to have been

13:08.040 --> 13:08.680
passing by.

13:08.940 --> 13:14.260
She made a very grand appearance, having on a high head-dress a rich gown of velvet, and

13:14.260 --> 13:19.320
a rough done-up with a famous yellow starch, of which Anne Turner, her especial friend,

13:19.320 --> 13:24.500
had taught her the secret, before the last good lady had been hanged for Sir Thomas Overbury's

13:24.500 --> 13:24.940
murder.

13:25.660 --> 13:29.900
Whether the witch had read the minister's thoughts or no, she came to a full stop, looking

13:29.900 --> 13:35.160
shrewdly in his face, smiled craftily, and, though little given to converse with clergymen,

13:35.340 --> 13:36.300
began a conversation.

13:36.800 --> 13:41.380
"'So, reverend sir, you have made a visit into the forest,' observed the witch-lady,

13:41.580 --> 13:43.120
nodding her high head-dress to him.

13:43.380 --> 13:47.940
"'The next time, I pray, you allow me only a fair warning, and I shall be proud to bear

13:47.940 --> 13:48.360
you company.

13:48.700 --> 13:53.600
Without taking over much upon myself, my good word will go far towards gaining any strange

13:53.600 --> 13:57.580
gentleman a fair reception from younger potente you want off.'

13:58.440 --> 14:03.400
"'I profess, madam,' answered the clergyman, with a grave obscience, such as the lady's

14:03.400 --> 14:08.200
rank demanded, and his own good breeding made imperative, "'I profess on my conscience

14:08.200 --> 14:12.400
and character that I am utterly bewildered as touching the purport of your words.

14:12.500 --> 14:15.120
I went not into the forest to seek a potentate.

14:15.120 --> 14:20.140
Neither do I, at any future time, design a visit thither, with a view of gaining the

14:20.140 --> 14:21.340
favour of such personage.

14:21.700 --> 14:25.980
My one sufficient object was to greet that pious friend of mine, the apostle Elliot,

14:26.280 --> 14:29.980
and rejoice with him over the many precious souls he hath won from heathen-dom.

14:30.300 --> 14:35.660
"'Ha, ha, ha!' cackled the old witch-lady, still nodding her high head-dress at the minister.

14:36.180 --> 14:39.080
"'Well, well, we must talk thus in the daytime.

14:39.400 --> 14:44.040
You carry it off like an old hand, but at midnight in the forest we shall have other

14:44.040 --> 14:45.360
talk together.'

14:45.360 --> 14:50.220
She passed on with her aged stateliness, but often turning back her head and smiling at

14:50.220 --> 14:53.940
him, like one willing to recognize a secret intimacy of connection.

14:54.660 --> 14:59.360
"'Have I then sold myself,' thought the minister, to the fiend whom, if men say true,

14:59.560 --> 15:03.580
this yellow-starched and velveted old hag has chosen for her prince and master?

15:04.040 --> 15:05.400
The wretched minister!

15:05.540 --> 15:07.420
He had made a bargain very like it.

15:07.540 --> 15:12.660
Tempted by a dream of happiness, he had yielded himself with deliberate choice, as he had

15:12.660 --> 15:13.620
never done before.

15:14.000 --> 15:19.980
To what he knew was deadly sin, and the infectious poison of that sin had been thus rapidly diffused

15:19.980 --> 15:21.240
throughout his moral system.

15:21.840 --> 15:26.760
It had stupefied all blessed impulses, and awakened into vivid life the whole brotherhood

15:26.760 --> 15:27.320
of bad ones.

15:27.800 --> 15:33.860
Scorn, bitterness, unprovoked malignity, gratuitous desire of ill, ridicule of whatever was good

15:33.860 --> 15:37.380
and holy, all awoke to tempt, even while they frightened him.

15:37.740 --> 15:42.400
And his encounter with old mistress Hibbins, if it were a real incident, did but show its

15:42.400 --> 15:46.620
sympathy and fellowship with wicked mortals, and the world of perverted spirits.

15:47.760 --> 15:52.280
He had by this time reached his dwelling on the edge of the burial ground, and, hastening

15:52.280 --> 15:54.240
up the stairs, took refuge in his study.

15:54.760 --> 15:58.800
The minister was glad to have reached this shelter without first betraying himself to

15:58.800 --> 16:03.940
the world by any of those strange and wicked eccentricities to which he had been continually

16:03.940 --> 16:05.980
impelled while passing through the streets.

16:06.500 --> 16:11.100
He entered the accustomed room and looked around him on its books, its windows, its

16:11.100 --> 16:16.220
fireplace, and the tapestrid comfort of the walls, with the same perception of strangeness

16:16.220 --> 16:20.900
that had haunted him throughout his walk from the forest dell into the town and thitherward.

16:21.500 --> 16:22.800
Here he had studied and written.

16:23.380 --> 16:26.720
Here gone through fast and vigil, and come forth half alive.

16:27.180 --> 16:28.280
Here striven to pray.

16:28.600 --> 16:30.740
Here borne a hundred thousand agonies.

16:31.000 --> 16:35.560
There was the Bible in its rich old Hebrew, with Moses and the prophets speaking to him,

16:35.820 --> 16:37.100
and God's voice through all.

16:37.420 --> 16:41.920
There on the table, with the inky pen beside it, was an unfinished sermon, with a sentence

16:41.920 --> 16:46.400
broken in the midst, where his thoughts had ceased to gush upon the page two days before.

16:46.860 --> 16:51.120
He knew that it was himself, the thin and white-cheeked minister, who had done and suffered

16:51.120 --> 16:54.300
these things, and written thus far into the election sermon.

16:54.680 --> 16:59.700
But he seemed to stand apart and eye this former self with scornful pity, but half envious

16:59.700 --> 17:00.340
curiosity.

17:00.740 --> 17:01.700
That self was gone.

17:01.980 --> 17:06.520
Another man had returned out of the forest, a wiser one, with a knowledge of hidden mysteries

17:06.520 --> 17:11.680
which the simplicity of the former never could have reached, a bitter kind of knowledge that.

17:12.240 --> 17:16.380
While occupied with these reflections, a knock came at the door of the study, and the minister

17:16.380 --> 17:21.440
said, Come in, not wholly devoid of an idea that he might behold an evil spirit.

17:21.680 --> 17:22.620
And so he did.

17:23.000 --> 17:25.060
It was old Roger Chillingworth that entered.

17:25.400 --> 17:29.580
The minister stood white and speechless, with one hand on the Hebrew scriptures, and the

17:29.580 --> 17:30.860
other spread upon his breast.

17:31.660 --> 17:33.840
Welcome home, reverend sir, said the physician.

17:34.250 --> 17:36.700
And how found you that godly man, the apostle Elliot?

17:37.080 --> 17:41.080
But methinks, dear sir, you look pale, as if the travel through the wilderness had been

17:41.080 --> 17:41.980
too sore for you.

17:42.360 --> 17:46.280
Will not my aid be requisite to put you in heart and strength to preach your election

17:46.280 --> 17:46.640
sermon?

17:47.180 --> 17:50.100
Nay, I think not so, rejoined the reverend Mr. Dimmesdale.

17:50.380 --> 17:55.140
My journey and the sight of the holy apostle yonder, and the free air which I have breathed,

17:55.320 --> 17:58.380
have done me good, after so long confinement in my study.

17:58.820 --> 18:03.320
I think to need no more of your drugs, my kind physician, good though they be, and administered

18:03.320 --> 18:04.420
by a friendly hand.

18:05.120 --> 18:09.360
At this time Roger Chillingworth was looking at the minister with the grave and intent

18:09.360 --> 18:11.600
regard of a physician towards his patient.

18:12.140 --> 18:17.000
But in spite of this outward show, the latter was almost convinced of the old man's knowledge,

18:17.300 --> 18:22.420
or at least his confident suspicion, with respect to his own interview with Hester Prynne.

18:22.780 --> 18:27.320
The physician knew then that in the minister's regard he was no longer a trusted friend,

18:27.600 --> 18:28.840
but his bitterest enemy.

18:29.340 --> 18:33.300
So much being known, it would appear natural that a part of it should be expressed.

18:33.520 --> 18:39.120
It is singular, however, how long a time often passes before words embody things, and with

18:39.120 --> 18:44.240
what security two persons, who chose to avoid a certain subject, may approach its very verge

18:44.240 --> 18:46.040
and retire without disturbing it.

18:46.160 --> 18:50.680
Thus the minister felt no apprehension that Roger Chillingworth would touch and express

18:50.680 --> 18:54.340
words upon the real position which they sustained towards one another.

18:54.860 --> 18:58.540
Yet did the physician, in his dark way, creep frightfully near the secret.

18:59.420 --> 19:04.300
Were it not better, he said, that you use my poor skill tonight, verily dear sir, we

19:04.300 --> 19:08.520
must take pains to make you strong and vigorous for this occasion of the election discourse.

19:08.980 --> 19:13.360
The people look for great things from you, apprehending that another year may come about

19:13.360 --> 19:14.780
and find their master gone.

19:15.460 --> 19:20.280
Yes, to another world replied the minister, with pious resignation, heaven granted that

19:20.280 --> 19:25.440
better one, for, in good sooth, I hardly think to tarry with my flock through the fleeting

19:25.440 --> 19:26.520
seasons of another year.

19:26.840 --> 19:31.080
But touching your medicine, kind sir, in my present frame of body, I need it not.

19:31.440 --> 19:33.580
I joy to hear it, administered the physician.

19:33.880 --> 19:38.620
It may be that my remedies, so long administered in vain, begin now to take due effect.

19:39.000 --> 19:43.440
Happy man were I, and well deserving of New England's gratitude, could I achieve this

19:43.440 --> 19:43.720
cure.

19:44.200 --> 19:49.100
I thank you from my heart, most watchful friend, said Reverend Mr. Dimmesdale, with a solemn

19:49.100 --> 19:49.420
smile.

19:49.880 --> 19:53.280
I thank you, and can but requite your good deeds with my prayers.

19:53.980 --> 19:58.600
A good man's prayers are golden recompense, rejoined old Roger Chillingworth, as he took

19:58.600 --> 19:59.020
his leave.

19:59.480 --> 20:04.060
Yea, they are the current gold coin of the New Jerusalem, with the King's own mint mark

20:04.060 --> 20:04.660
on them.

20:05.760 --> 20:10.600
Left alone, the minister summoned a servant of the house, and requested food, which, being

20:10.600 --> 20:13.280
set before him, he ate with ravenous appetite.

20:13.560 --> 20:18.160
Then flinging the already written pages of the election sermon into the fire, he forthwith

20:18.160 --> 20:22.580
began another, which he wrote with such an impulsive flow of thought and emotion, that

20:22.580 --> 20:27.160
he fancied himself inspired, and only wondered that heaven should see fit to transmit the

20:27.160 --> 20:31.460
grand and solemn music of its oracles through so foul an organ-pipe as he.

20:31.940 --> 20:37.040
However, leaving that mystery to solve itself, or go unsolved for ever, he drove his task

20:37.040 --> 20:39.080
onward with earnest haste and ecstasy.

20:39.880 --> 20:44.260
Thus the night fled away, as if it were a winged steed, and he careering on it.

20:44.630 --> 20:49.620
Morning came and peeped, blushing, through the curtains, and at last sunrise through

20:49.620 --> 20:54.140
a golden beam into the study, and laid it right across the minister's bedazzled eyes.

20:54.500 --> 20:59.000
There he was, with the pen still between his fingers, and a vast immeasurable tract of

20:59.000 --> 21:00.820
written space behind him.

